# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-civil-war
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The **1811 German Coast uprising** was a slave rebellion which occurred in the Territory of Orleans on January 8–10, 1811.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] It occurred on the east bank of the Mississippi River in the modern-day Louisiana parishes of St.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebellion was the largest of its kind in the history of the United States.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels killed two white slave owner family members, but the confrontations with the U.S. military and local militiamen who were sent to suppress the rebellion, combined with post-trial executions, resulted in the deaths of 95 rebels.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 8, between 64 and 125 slaves ignited a fight for freedom and marched from plantations in and near present-day LaPlace, Louisiana on the German Coast towards New Orleans.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] More people escaped slavery and joined them along the way, and some accounts claimed a total of 200 to 500 people escaped and participated in the rebellion.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] During their two-day, 20 mi (32 km)-long march the rebels, armed mostly with improvised weapons, burned five plantations along with several sugarhouses and crop fields.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After a few planters were killed and others attacked, White settlers led by U.S. officials formed militia companies.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In battle on January 10 they killed 40 to 45 of the people escaping slavery, while suffering no fatalities themselves, then hunted down and killed several other people without trial.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Over the next two weeks, White planters and U.S. officials interrogated, tried, executed, and decapitated an additional 44 people escaping slavery who had been captured.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Executions were generally by hanging or firing squad.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Heads were displayed on pikes to intimidate others.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration in January of the uprising, in which they have been joined by some descendants of participants in the revolt.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sugar boom on what was known as Louisiana's German Coast (named for immigrants in the 1720s) began after the American Revolutionary War, while the area near New Orleans was still controlled by Spain.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the 1780s Jean Saint Malo, an escaped slave, established a colony of maroons in the swamps below New Orleans, which eventually led Spanish officials to send militia to capture him.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Saint Malo became a folk hero after his execution in New Orleans on June 19, 1784.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] A decade later, during the height of the French Revolution, Spanish officials discovered a slave conspiracy at Pointe Coupee (established by French settlers around 1720 between Natchez and New Orleans).
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] That slave uprising during the Easter holidays was suppressed before it came to fruition and resulted in 23 executions by hanging (with the severed heads then displayed on the road to New Orleans), and 31 additional slaves were flogged and sent to serve hard labor in other Spanish outposts.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the Haitian Revolution, planters established similar lucrative sugarcane plantations in the Gulf Coast area, resulting in a dense slave population.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They converted from cotton and indigo plantations to sugarcane, so that by 1802, 70 sugar plantations produced over 3,000 tons annually.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some accounts claimed blacks outnumbered whites by nearly five to one by 1810, and about 90% of whites in the area enslaved people.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] More than half of those enslaved may have been born outside Louisiana, many in Africa, where various European nations established slave trading outposts and Kongo was ripped apart by civil wars.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the U.S. negotiated the Louisiana Purchase in 1803, both the Marquis de Lafayette and James Monroe declined to become the governor of the Territory of Orleans.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] President Thomas Jefferson then turned to a fellow Virginian, William C.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne, whom he appointed on an interim basis and who arrived in New Orleans with 350 volunteers and 18 boats.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne struggled with the area's diverse population, particularly because he spoke neither French nor Spanish.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The population also included a larger proportion of native Africans among the slaves than elsewhere in the U.S.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In addition, the mixed-race Creole and French-speaking population grew markedly with refugees from Haiti (and their slaves) following the successful Haitian Revolution.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Claiborne was not used to a society with the number of free people of color that Louisiana had, but he worked to continue their role in the militia that had been established under Spanish rule.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Long-term French Creole residents complained to Washington, D.C., about Claiborne and new U.S. settlers in the territory, and wanted no part of President Jefferson's plan to pay 30,000 Americans to move into the new territory and amalgamate with the residents.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, by 1805, a delegation led by Jean Noël Destréhan went to Washington to complain about the "oppressive and degrading" form of the territorial government, but President Madison continued to support Claiborne, who had expressed great doubts about the planters' honesty and trustworthiness.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Lastly, Claiborne suspected that the Spanish in nearby West Florida might encourage an insurrection.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thus, he struggled to establish and maintain his authority.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In the overall Territory of Orleans, from 1803 to 1811, the free black population nearly tripled, to 5,000, with 3,000 arriving as migrants from Haiti (via Cuba) in 1809–1810.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In Saint-Domingue they had enjoyed certain rights as *gens de couleur*, including owning slaves themselves.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Furthermore, between 1790 and 1810, slave traders brought around 20,000 enslaved Africans to New Orleans.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The masters and slaves were virtually all Catholic.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The waterways and bayous around New Orleans and Lake Pontchartrain made transportation and trade possible but also provided easy escapes and nearly impenetrable hiding places for runaway slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some maroon colonies continued for years within several miles of New Orleans.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] With the spread of ideas of freedom from the French and Haitian Revolutions, European Americans worried about slave uprisings, particularly in the Louisiana area.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 1805, they heard a traveling Frenchman was preaching about liberty, equality, and fraternity to the French-speaking slaves, and arrested him as dangerous.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] A group of slaves met on January 6, 1811.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] It was a period when work had relaxed on the plantations after the fierce weeks of the sugar harvest and processing.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] As planter James Brown testified weeks later, "The black Quamana [Kwamena, meaning "born on Saturday"], owned by Mr.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Brown, and the mulatto Harry, owned by Messrs.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Kenner and Henderson, were at the home of Manuel Andry on the night of Saturday–Sunday of the current month in order to deliberate with the mulatto Charles Deslondes, chief of the brigands." Slaves had spread word of the planned uprising among the slaves at plantations up and down the German Coast.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The revolt began on January 8 at the Andry plantation.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After striking and badly wounding Andry, the slaves killed his son Gilbert.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] "An attempt was made to assassinate me by the stroke of an axe", Andry wrote.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] "My poor son has been ferociously murdered by a horde of brigands who from my plantation to that of Mr.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The approximately 15 slaves at Andry's plantation, about 30 miles (50 km) upriver from New Orleans, joined another eight slaves from the next-door plantation of the widows of Jacques and Georges Deslondes.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] This was the home plantation of Charles Deslondes, a slave driver (a slave overseer of other slaves) later described by one of the captured slaves as the "principal chief of the brigands".
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Small groups of slaves joined from every plantation the rebels passed.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Witnesses remarked on their organized march.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They carried mostly pikes, hoes, and axes, but few firearms, and they marched to drums while some carried flags.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Approximately 10–25% of any given plantation's slave population joined with them.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the plantation of James Brown, Kook, one of the most active participants and key figures in the story of the uprising, joined the insurrection.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] At the next plantation down, Kook attacked and killed François Trépagnier with an axe.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] He was the second and last planter killed in the rebellion.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After the band of slaves passed the LaBranche plantation, they stopped at the home of the local physician.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Finding him gone, Kook set his house on fire.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some planters testified at the trials in parish courts that they were warned by slaves of the uprising.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Others regularly stayed in New Orleans, where many had town houses, and trusted their plantations to overseers to run.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Planters quickly crossed the Mississippi River to escape the insurrection and to raise a militia.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] As those escaping moved downriver, they passed larger plantations, from which other slaves joined them.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Numerous slaves joined the insurrection from the Meuillion plantation, the largest and wealthiest plantation on the German Coast.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The rebels laid waste to Meuillion's house.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They tried to set it on fire, but a slave named Bazile fought the fire and saved the house.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising started in present-day LaPlace and followed a 20-mile trek on the old River Road through the present-day towns of Montz, Norco, New Sarpy, Destrehan, St.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Rose and ended at much of what had once been the Kenner and Henderson Plantations and is now Rivertown and Louis Armstrong International Airport in Kenner.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] After nightfall the escaping slaves reached Cannes-Brulées, about 15 miles (24 km) northwest of New Orleans.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The men had traveled between 14 and 22 miles (23 and 35 km), a march that probably took them seven to ten hours.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By some accounts, they numbered "some 200 slaves", although other accounts estimated up to 500.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] As typical of revolts of most classes, free or slave, the insurgent slaves were mostly young men between the ages of 20 and 30.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] They represented primarily lower-skilled occupations on the sugar plantations, where slaves labored in difficult conditions with a low life expectancy.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Despite his injuries, Andry crossed the river and made contact with other planters, raising a militia and pursuing the escaping slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By noon on January 9, the residents of New Orleans had heard about the insurrection.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By sunset, General Wade Hampton I, Commodore John Shaw, and Claiborne sent two volunteer militia companies, 30 US Army soldiers, and 40 US Navy sailors to fight the escaping slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] By about 4 a.m. on January 10, this force had reached Jacques Fortier's plantation, where Hampton thought the escaped slaves had encamped overnight.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] However, the escaped slaves had started back upriver about two hours earlier, had traveled about 15 miles (24 km) back up the coast, and had neared Bernard Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] There, planter Charles Perret, in cooperation with Andry and Judge St.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, had assembled a militia of about 80 men from the river's opposite side.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] At about 9 o'clock, this militia force discovered escaping slaves moving toward high ground on Bernoudy's plantation.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret ordered his men to attack the escaping slaves, which he later wrote numbered about 200 men, about half on horseback.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] (Most accounts said only the leaders were mounted, and historians believe it unlikely the escaping men could have gathered so many mounts.) Within a half-hour, 40 to 45 escaping people had been killed; the remainder slipped away into the woods and swamps.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Perret's and Andry's militias tried to pursue them despite the difficult terrain.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] On January 11, the militia, assisted by Native American trackers as well as hunting dogs, captured Deslondes, whom Andry considered "the principal leader of the bandits." A slave driver and son of a white man and a slave, Deslondes received no trial or interrogation.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The following day Pierre Griffee and Hans Wimprenn, who were thought the murderers of M.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] François Trépagnier, were captured, killed, and their heads decapitated for delivery to the Andry estate.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Major Milton and the dragoons from Baton Rouge arrived and provided support for the militia, since Hampton believed them supported by Spanish authorities in West Florida.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Having suppressed the insurrection, the planters and government officials continued to search for people who had escaped.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Those captured later were interrogated and jailed before trials.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Officials convened three tribunals: one at Destrehan Plantation in St.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, and the third in New Orleans (Orleans Parish).
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Destrehan trials, overseen by Judge Pierre Bauchet St.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Martin, resulted in the execution of 18 of 21 captured people by firing squad.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Some slaves testified against others, but others refused to testify or submit to the all-planter tribunal.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In New Orleans, Commodore Shaw presumed that "but few of those who have been taken were acquitted." The New Orleans trials resulted in the conviction and summary executions of 11 more slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Three were publicly hanged in the *Place d'Armes*, now Jackson Square.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] One of those spared was a 13-year-old boy, who was ordered to witness another man's death and then received 30 lashes.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Another escaped person was treated with leniency because his uncle turned him in and begged for mercy.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The sentence of a third person was commuted because of the valuable information he had given.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heads of those executed were put on pikes and the mutilated bodies of dead rebels displayed to intimidate other slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The naval officer Samuel Hambleton described the heads posted on stakes that lined the levee as follows, "They were brung up here for the sake of their Heads, which decorate our Levee, all the way up the coast.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] U.S. territorial law provided no appeal from a parish court's ruling, even in cases involving imposition of a death sentence on a slave.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In fact, Claiborne did commute two death sentences, those of Henry and Theodore, each referred by the Orleans Parish court.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] No record has been found of any referral from the court in St.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Charles Parish, or of any refusal by the governor of an application for clemency.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Militias killed about 95 slaves between the battle, subsequent summary apprehensions and executions, as well as by execution after trials.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] From the trial records, most of the leaders appeared to have been mixed-race Creoles or mulattoes, although numerous slaves were native-born Africans.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Fifty-six of the slaves captured on January 10 and involved in the revolt were returned to their masters, who may have punished them but wanted their valuable laborers back to work.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Thirty more escaping slaves were captured and returned to their masters after planters determined they had been forced to join the revolt by Deslondes and his men.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The heirs of Meuillon petitioned the legislature for permission to free the mulatto slave Bazile, who had worked to preserve his master's plantation.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Not all the slaves supported insurrection, knowing the trouble it could bring and not wanting to see their homes and communities destroyed.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising was short-lived and quickly crushed by local authorities.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Showing planter influence, the legislature of the Territory of Orleans approved compensation of $300 to planters for each escaping slave killed or executed.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The territory gratefully accepted the presence of U.S. troops after the revolt.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The national press covered the insurrection, with some Northerners seeing it arising out of the wrongs suffered under slavery.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] Since 1995, the African American History Alliance of Louisiana has led an annual commemoration at Norco in January, where they have been joined by some descendants of members of the revolt.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] While the Destrehan Plantation tour concentrates on architecture and white lifestyle and family histories, a small museum in a converted slave cabin (not on the standard tour) features folk paintings of the 1811 uprising.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] More recently, the Whitney Plantation, in St.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] John the Baptist Parish, opened in 2014 and is the first plantation museum in the country dedicated to the slave experience.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The Whitney Plantation includes a memorial and information to commemorate the 1811 Slave Uprising of the German Coast.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2015, artist Dread Scott began organizing a massive re-enactment of the uprising; the 26 mile, 2-day event took place in November 2019.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The uprising is featured in Talene Monahon's 2020 play about historical reenactment, *How to Load a Musket*.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] In 2021, the 1811 Kid Ory Historic House opened on the site of Woodland Plantation in LaPlace, which is in the National Register of Historic Places of the United States.
[src:american-civil-war/1811-german-coast-uprising] The museum is dedicated to the German Coast uprising and to Kid Ory, an American jazz composer, trombonist, and bandleader born there in 1886.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The **Fiji Expedition of 1840** was an exploring and surveying expedition, which itself was a part of the wider United States Exploring Expedition (a.k.a. the **Wilkes expedition** or the **U.S.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.**) that occurred from May 4 to August 11, 1840.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It produced several scientific and cultural breakthroughs in realms such as cartography, oceanography, volcanology, anthropology, ethnography, ethnology, philology, linguistics, geology, taxonomy, trade, diplomacy, toponymy, epidemiology, pathology and Christian missionary work.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It also was known for two separate punitive expeditions against separate groups of Fijians.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. under the command of Lieutenant Charles Wilkes had just discovered that Antarctica was a continent, and finished surveying Wilkes Land.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes was facing a significant deadline.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was originally given a deadline of 3 years to conduct the necessary research for all the allotted study location goals for the expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Unfortunately for him he only had two months to conduct the studies for Fiji expedition, then he would immediately have to journey to the Columbia river expeditions to finish the rest of the studies for the rest of the year.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If Wilkes did not, the sailors' and marines' enlistment service would expire, and the expedition's future would have been put in jeopardy.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This situation put Wilkes under immense pressure.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As it was, besides the Columbia river expedition, the Fiji expedition was considered the most paramount research destination for several reasons.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] New England merchants and whalers frequented Fiji for its whale and sandalwood, and competed with the British and the French for the bêche-de-mer populations to sell in China.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Fiji possessed many uncharted reefs, rocks, and currents, with a culture well known for its cannibalism (in fact for a while Fiji was also known as the Cannibal Isles) and a noted penchant for dragging boats to shore and killing all on board.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] No dependable navigation charts existed, and in the 12 years prior to 1840, 8 ships (5 of them being American) had been destroyed in the area.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] These conditions made travel to and around these Islands so precarious, the East India Marine Society of Salem, Massachusetts, United States had petitioned the federal government for local charts for sailors navigating these waters.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Although surveying was the primary reason for the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. also brought along a group of scientists which were also deployed for the Fiji expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now that the Antarctic discoveries were finished, Wilkes' fleet traveled to Sydney, Australia, then to the Bay of Islands, New Zealand, and finally they rendezvoused at Tongatapu, in Tonga, and prepared for their next mission in Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes had already had his four ships refitted at Sydney.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His current fleet at the time of the Fiji expedition consisted of Wilkes' flagship the USS *Vincennes* (sloop-of-war, 780 tons, 18 guns), the USS *Peacock* (sloop-of-war, 650 tons, 22 guns), the USS *Porpoise* (brig, 230 tons, 10 guns), and the USS *Flying Fish* (schooner, 96 tons, 2 guns).
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Furthermore, Wilkes had at least a dozen gigs, cutters, and whaleboats prepared for travel against the hazardous reefs.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes' fleet set sail out of Nukuʻalofa on May 4, 1840.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He dispatched the *Porpoise* under Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold to the Lau Group of the Fiji Islands, while the rest of the fleet went to the Koro Sea.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The 3 ships headed for the Island of Ovalau, but by the morning of May 7, the *Flying Fish* under the command of Lieutenant George Sinclair went missing, after it got caught on a reef.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes pressed on with the *Peacock* and the *Vincennes* and anchored by the village Levuka.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon Wilkes arrival, a white shipwrecked survivor of the Oneo a Nantucket man named David Whippey and one of his sons paddled up to the *Vincennes.* Whippey was what was called a beachcomber, which in this context meant a "tame white man" to the Fijians.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was a sort of mercenary, military advisor, and translator.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The earliest beachcomber Charlie Savage and those like him taught Fijians how to use fire arms.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This revolutionized Fijian warfare, and they were greatly valued by war chiefs, who rewarded them with riches and women.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey had risen to the title of "Mata-ki-Bau" (the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes arranged for Whippey to have him meet the chief or "Tu'i" of Levuku.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes bestowed several gifts upon the chief, who in gratitude and with Whippey's aid sent a message to Tanoa high King *Vunivalu* of Bau (called "Old Snuff by the local whites) and head of the notorious Lasakau sea warriors, and asked to meet with him.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a messenger was sent, Whippey took Wilkes and 25 of his officers and naturalists (including the commander of the *Peacock* Lieutenant William L.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson and Navy Geographer and passed midshipman Henry Eld), along with an entourage of natives, on a tour and hike of Mount Nadelaiovalau.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At the top of the mountain Wilkes and his scientists could clearly see the surrounding area including nearby reefs and other nearby landmarks.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The group set out right away making charts, sketches, measurements for recording, and collecting plant and animal specimens.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 8 Wilkes deployed two surveying parties on boats.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One was to be led by Lieutenant James Alden Jr. who would leave Ovalau to explore the northern shore of Viti Levu Island.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The second boat was led by Lieutenant George F.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons, who in turn scouted the south shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave the officer further orders that after exploring their respective shores that they should assemble at the Island of Malolo which was to the west of Viti Levu.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day Lieutenant Sinclair arrived with the *Flying Fish* at Levuka and reported to Wilkes.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 11 Wilkes decided to build an observatory of tents, houses, and a small research garden.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was situated 30 feet above the beach on a peak near Levuku village, and above Vi Tonga village as a forward operating center for the Fiji Expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The observatory was erected on May 11, with guards surrounding the perimeter.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 12, Chief Tanoa arrived in a finely decorated 100 foot, double hulled, outrigger canoe with a sail and a 40-man crew.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He boarded the Vincennes and through Whippey was able to negotiate a trade deal between Bau and the United States.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A few days later, Wilkes received Seru Epenisa Cakobau the son and crown prince of Tanoa, who further cemented bonds of the Bau nation and the expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Seru would one day come to unite the Kingdoms of Bau, Rewa, and Naitasiri into the short lived Kingdom of Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Tanoa was the King of Bau, he exercised the greatest influence among all the other kingdoms of the islands of Fiji, Tui Levuku was in charge of Ovalau Island.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With the aid of Whippey, Tui Levuku helped the Americans maintain their supply lines, trade with Levuku village, and receive information through the first six weeks of the Fiji expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a few says an Irish beachcomber named Paddy O'Connell entered Wilkes, tent on Ovalu.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell attempted to hire himself out to Wilkes, but Wilkes dismissed him at first.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, a single story caught his interest.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell informed Wiles that he was a witness to the murder of several of the crew of the American bêche-de-mer merchant ship the *Charles Doggett* in August 1834, on Ono Island.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes learned that a Fijian chief named Veidovi was the man who organized the attack.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] According to O'Connell he was a crewman of the *Charles Doggett* when the incident occurred.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In this instance Captain Bachelor of the *Charles Doggett* made a contract with a chief named Veidovi for *bêche-de-mer* on Rewa.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the *Charles Doggett* reached Rewa, it was agreed that a minor chief would willingly be taken hostage for the protection of the Westerners while they set up a *bêche-de-mer* house on shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the chief feigned sickness and was allowed to return to shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the minor chief returned with Veidovi and some of his men and asked for medicine at the *bêche-de-mer* house.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mate, eight other men, and a boy came ashore, all except one were killed, robbed, and the house was house set on fire.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day the captain, through O'Connell, was able to negotiate for all the bodies back except an African American crewmate whose body was eaten.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later O'Connell became a beachcomber and discovered that while Veidovi was the primary perpetrator of this attack, the other chiefs of Rewa and especially Veidovi's kin endorsed the killings.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon hearing this story Wilkes became angry and sent O'Connell to Lieutenant Hudson on the *Peacock* to arrest Veidovi.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] O'Connell met Hudson and gave him Wilkes' orders.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair of them set out for Rewa in Viti Levu where Veidovi lived.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was there that Hudson eventually met with King Kania or Roko Tui Dreketi/King of Rewa and Methodist missionaries of the English Wesleyan Mission who helped him get the lay of the land.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After assessing the political landscape, Hudson quickly concocted a plan to trap Veidovi.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On May 21 Hudson invited the King Kania and his three brothers on board the *Peacock* to a welcoming reception.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Between 70 and over 100 local Fijians showed up along with the Tui Dreketi himself, but Veidovi was noticeably absent.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson lured the native royals into his cabin with an offering of a meal and then called for battle stations.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The royals were split away from their retainers.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson promised mercy to the chiefs in exchange for them delivering Veidovi to them, and causing no harm to the local missionaries.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a spout of protest the King Kania agreed, and two of the chiefs brothers were released to arrest Veidovi dead or alive.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The following day Veidovi arrived and agreed to go quietly in exchange for the freedom of his family and their families respectively.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson took Veidovi to his personal cabin for interrogation and Veidovi openly conceded to orchestrating the *Charles Doggett* killings.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi explained that he lured the mate of the ship into a trip and feigned a friendly greeting to the mate of the ship.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then his men seized the mate and clubbed him to death, and then proceeded to kill more of the ship hands.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi added that his motivations were to acquire firearms and that he was only following his culture in that "...he had only followed the Fegee customs and done what his people had often done before.".
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson decided to punish Veidovi by forcing him to travel with the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and then live in America for a few years, where he would learn to be civilized and not kill white people.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Veidovi was dismayed, since as a chief he had 55 wives and numerous children that he would have to leave behind.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hudson then headed for Kadavu Island where it was said more of the perpetrators of the attack on the *Charles Doggett* resided.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, the wind was against him, and suffering for a lack of time in his other duties for the expedition, Hudson satisfied himself with the capture of Veidovi and returned to Levuka.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Word traveled fast of Veidovi's capture, it spread to the village of Levuka, and then to Wilkes himself.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey and Tui Levuku soon caught wind of a plot to capture Wilkes in order to entice and exchange of prisoners (Wilkes for Veidovi).
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The suspected perpatrtors would have been King Tanoa who was allies with King Kania.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the Mountains of Ovalau resided the Livoni tribe who were allied with Tanoa.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes remained armed, furnished himself an escort, he ordered 40 men to reinforce the observatory.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes then took Seru hostage on board the *Vincennes*, repositioned the guns of the *Vincennes* to a more defensible position.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes also brought his dog Sydney with him (which terrified the natives), and an attempted kidnapping never materialized.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In early June, a British expedition consisting of the HMS Sulphur (1826) HMS Starling (1829)) commanded by Captain Edward Belcher arrived in Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was conducting his own separate surveying expedition and had just come from the Vavaʻu island group in Tonga.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher traveled to Rewa where the Sulphur had lost a rudder from hitting a reef.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After Belcher's expedition encountered other members of the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. and through messengers, Wilkes gave Belcher a spare rudder from the fleet.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, Wilkes came to meet Belcher aboard his ship, and they spoke together in Belcher's cabin.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, despite Wilkes' goodwill in offering Belcher an extra rudder, Belcher was less than pleased to see him.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Belcher was required to pay port charges due to the trade deal that he had set up between the U.S. and chief Tanoa.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The meeting did not accomplish much, although Wilkes found out that Belcher had explored the Columbia River the year before in 1839, and based on Belcher's descriptions Wilkes believed he would definitely need to extend the length of the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The two parted cordially and Belcher and his ships later sailed to Vanuatu.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Chief Tui Levuku decided to honor the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. with a traditional Club dance/Meke called the Meke I Wau or Meke Mada on June 24 at Levuku village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Over a hundred Fijians and their chiefs from Levuku and other nearby villages attended.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans were directed to the Mbure/temple, or spirit-house, which had an elevated platform where they could more easily observe the festivities.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The location overlooked the village from where they observed a low square stone wall on the opposite end of the street.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On one end many Fijians sat down awaiting the performance and on the opposite were several Fijian musicians.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually a "Feejee Clown" emerged in the center of the crowd, and began to galivant and dance wildly, to the delight and laughter of all.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown's body was completely enveloped with green and brown leaves and several vines, except for his face to which he wore a mask.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes stated that to him the mask looked somewhat like the face of a bear.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The mask was painted black on one half and orange on the other.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The clown danced with one large club in one hand and a shorter one on the other.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the clown performed, the musicians began to play with hand claps, sticks, and bamboo joints which made a soft drumming sound.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Roughly 100 club dancers were waiting behind a rock until they were ready.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they emerged in a column of two and began to proceed down the street at a slow three step pace.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They all wore the white *I-sala* turban typically worn by priests and chiefs as well as a white Masi tapa cloth to cover themselves.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Their sala were decorated with flowers and vines, and their faces were painted in various patterns of black and vermillion.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the dance columns advanced they split up from two columns to three and then to four and danced and swung their clubs in a variety of motions and poses.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They danced into the square and joined the clown and the musicians.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The dancers began singing with the musicians and their dances became more rapid and volatile, before they concluded their song and dance with a loud cry of "Wha---hoo".
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When the presentation had concluded the dancers laid their clubs down in a pile before the Americans as a gift to them, but they expected to receive gifts in return.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day Wilkes gave gifts on behalf of the expedition to Chief Tui Levuku so that he might distribute them.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after the end of the club dance festival, Wilkes decided to pack up the observatory and move on to other areas of the Fijian Islands.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Before the expeditions departure the purser Robert Waldron purchased and donated land for the construction of a Methodist mission school, with both a school house and chapel led by John Hunt.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following this, the *Vincennes* departed on the 28th of June, to survey the hot springs of Savusavu on the Island of Vanua Levu.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Peacock* had several accidents associated with or on it during this expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At Vita Levu the ship sustained considerable, but non fatal damages to its hull.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While one of the Peacocks cutter boats had overturned and sank.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point one man lost three fingers to an anchor chain.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On another occasion a man accidentally shot off his index finger.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A third sailor nearly had his leg entirely detached.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, another sailor had an accident while winding the capstan and broke his ribs.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, perhaps the worst accident occurred on June 29 when 2nd mate Joseph Baxter of the *bêche-de-mer* *Leonidas* unwittingly placed a gunpowder cartridge under his shirt while preparing to fire a cannon (for non offensive purposes).
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A spark flew off from the igniter and hit the cartridge the man was carrying which exploded over three pounds of gunpowder, and the man was badly charred from the ordeal.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Baxter was later transferred to the Peacock for medical attention.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He confessed that he was a French man whose real name was Vincent Boudet.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] During one occasion of the expedition the *Peacock* was off the coast of Tavea when a chief and his wife and an escort of three canoes approached the ship.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Hoping to antagonize the crew, the natives explained that they had captured three prisoners from an enemy village and had "roasted them and eaten part!".
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They displayed a piece of one of the bodies that had been preserved in plantain leaves to show the crew.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then they produced a half gnawed on skull to be exhibited.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crew also noticed one native eating an eyeball, with flesh dangling from his mouth.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Some of the men vomited at this spectacle.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later the Waldron bought the skull to be added to the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s artifact collection in exchange for some cloth.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] William Brackenridge the horticulturalist and Charles Pickering the naturalist teamed up to make several discoveries together while at Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] With their mutual cooperation, they discovered over 650 different plant species.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included a new species of tomato and poison ivy.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Pickering made the discovery that if the science team did not bring anything that appeared valuable to the natives, they could travel about the Islands without great fear of danger or harassment.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This gave them ample time an opportunity to conduct their research.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And Brackenridge, for his part, found the last existing variant of sandalwood on Fiji, which up until that point was thought to have been extinct from over harvesting.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Horatio Hale, the teams' philologist and anthropologist, documented over 5,600 words in the Fiji language and documented their craftsmanship in producing various canoes, dwellings, and pottery.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] James Dwight Dana the team's geologist made a titanic discovery in his field.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He proved Charles Darwin's theory of subsidence, which Darwin had spoken about publicly, but was formally addressed in his book *The Structure and Distribution of Coral Reefs*.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the theory of subsidence after a volcanic Island is formed and after a lengthy period of time a fringing reef forms along the edges or "fringes" of the Island.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After that and given more time the Island begins to erode and sink and a lagoon begins to form around the island and the fringing reef becomes a barrier reef.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then after further erosion and sinking over time the island sinks into the sea and only the reef and lagoon it forms remains becoming an atoll.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Darwin at first thought he could not adequately prove his theory, but Dana proved it by finding all 3 stages of reef formations on the islands of Cicia, Matuku, and Nanuku.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex.'s surgeons was able to study a number of local diseases endemic to Fiji on Ovalau, as well as the natives methods for treating them.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these diseases included a disease the Fijians of the time called "dthoke" which has similarities to both lupus and yaws, and may be mistaken for secondary stage syphilis.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another was a Fijian form of influenza called the "dandy cough" that the natives believe spread and mutated through contact with contact from white people, or as the Fijian's called them "Papalangi".
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox believed this influenza may have come from an influenza epidemic that had spread in the USA a few years before the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fox recorded reports from many local whites that about a tenth of the Fijian population had died during that time.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 11th, the *Vincenees*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* were surveying in Bua Bay, Bua, Vanua Levu.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes dispatched, Lieutenant Oliver Hazard Perry Jr.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] (of the Perry Family) and passed midshipman Samuel R.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox 20 miles southeast, to lead a two cutter survey to chart Solevu bay.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The pair and their crews had been stuck in the bay by a storm for numerous days, with dwindling supplies.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the boats were anchored a group of natives taunted them threateningly from the beach.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Eventually their food ran out and both Perry and Knox felt compelled to escape.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The winds blew hard as the crew made for the shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon disembarking the boat, the sailors were encircled by several natives with clubs, spears, and a small amount of firearms.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews gunpowder was wet and so if it came down to a fight the crew would need to resort to hand-to-hand combat.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in an unprecedented move by Western accounts the chief in charge of the natives took pity on the explorers.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Knox and his men swam back to Perry's boat, which became overloaded.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As night fell, the natives lit fires on the beach and occasionally took pot shots at Perry and his men.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the cover of night, the natives stealthily began diving and swimming to the boat, and attempted to either lift the anchor or cut the anchor chain to drag the boat ashore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The sailors began firing into the water, and eventually were able to capture two of the tribesmen who swam to the boat and made an effort to appear to be allies.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry suspected them as spies and so arrested them.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out they were both chiefs one of high rank and one of low rank.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon taking these men hostage, the natives on the shore made no more attempts to go after the boat that night.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was supposed that they feared the death of their chiefs.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When morning came Perry made a second attempt to escape the bay.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This time he attempted to maneuver his cutter around the shallow reefs and into the open ocean.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Natives, realizing what Perry was attempting to accomplish, assembled around the edges of the reef.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point the boat struck a reef and took on water.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men attempted to bail and keep their distance from the natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Perry was able to escape with his crew and prisoners.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 12, Perry met with the *Vincennes*, *Flying Fish*, and *Peacock* which had all rendezvoused at Bua Bay.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After learning what had happened, Wilkes assembled 11 boats, 80 men, and the *Flying Fis*h to exact retribution, and retrieve the stolen cutter.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The flotilla arrived in the afternoon at low tide.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the waters were shallow a mudflat had formed between Wilkes' ships and the stolen cutter.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes met with the chiefs representatives and used Whippey as a translator.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes commanded the natives to return the boat and all items that were in it.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were intimidated as up until this point in Fijian history there was never before a time when so many westerners had gathered threatening war.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The chief returned the boat, but did not return the boats equipment and belongings of the crew.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Outraged Wilkes landed most of his men armed with muskets, but remained on a gig from which he would direct a Congreve rocket.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes ordered the burning of Solevu village and the politically linked nearby village of Tye.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Combined the fighters of these villages were between 150 and 200 warriors.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, both the warriors and the populace fled into the hills and Wilkes fired rockets into the village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The villages were destroyed, but due to the simplicity of the villages' material, the structures would be repaired in a few weeks.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Aside from loss or damage to property no side suffered any casualties.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Following the burning of the villages, and in an act of good will, Wilkes released the two captured chiefs and bestowed them with valuable gifts.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] His logic was that they came bearing friendship and aid to Perry's crew.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was also done to demonstrate to the natives that hostility to Americans (and white people in general) would be met with vengeance, and cordiality met with reward.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. soon moved on from Solevu to the Mamanuca Islands to continue their survey mission, while the Vincennes and Peacock deployed to Muthuata Island.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Whippey informed Wilkes that this set of islands was particularly notorious for being perilous to westerners, as the residents of Malolo were noted for being pirates and the worst offenders of attacking foreigners.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes acknowledged the danger and made sure his boats were grouped together and well escorted.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He deployed three boats and the *Porpoise* and *Flying Fish* for this mission.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The boats were led by Lieutenants Alden, Emmons, and Joseph Underwood.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 22 the squadron reached Drawaqa Island at the southern most end of the Yasawa Islands.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent two boats led by Alden and Underwood to the middle of the Mamanucas, the *Porpoise* took the Western side, and the *Flying Fish* and Emmons' cutter took the Western end.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The goal was for all three groups to complete their surveying that day and then assemble together at Malolo Island the next day.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 24, Alden and Underwood finished their surveying without issue, and anchored on the east side of Malolo next to Malolo Lailai for the night.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning Underwood and Alden noticed the *Flying Fish* and Emmons boat anchored in the distant East along Malolo.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An hour later, Emmons boat approached Underwood and Alden's.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They inquired for food, but Emmons regrettably told them that the *Flying Fish* was entirely bereft of anymore supplies.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This distressed the officers as only a few days ago Wilkes had cut the food rations by a third due to low provision levels, and currently Underwood and Alden's men only had a few yams with them.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was decided to try and trade with the local natives for food.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood encountered a Fijian boy chief in the area, who was carrying war clubs which struck him as menacing, and so arrested him.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Later, he found a group of local natives and through a Māori interpreter named John Sac, Underwood negotiated for food.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood was able to negotiate a tentative deal between himself and the natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The village of Malolo was on the Southwest part of the island and the natives proposed making an exchange for a few hogs.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, in order to get them Underwood would have to accompany the natives and one of the boats would have to sail to the Southwestern part of the island to pick them up.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It turned out that the local chief's son was the man that Underwood had captured.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In light of this, Underwood agreed to travel with the natives to their village provided that the chiefs son stay with his boat as a captive and guarantee of Underwood's safety, and would be released when business was concluded.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood used his own boat (the *Leopard*) as it was smaller than Alden and Emmons cutters and could more easily go over the shallows without getting trapped.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He left all but three of his muskets with the *Porpoise* in order to further reduce weight and increase the ease of travel.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This was actually against the standing orders that Wilkes had laid out for safety, but Underwood did not believe that the Fijians were as dangerous as was commonly supposed.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood brought Sac with him to translate, along with six other men.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the men stayed with the *Leopard* (commanded by Alden) and their hostage on the beach.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood met a group of natives near the village by a tree.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tree had many throwing and maiming clubs tied to the branches, and two thin hogs next to it.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood tried to barter for the swine, but he was informed that no transaction could be made without the chiefs approval.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After half an hour the chief appeared after returning from a fishing trip.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Chief demanded a musket with ammo and powder in exchange for the hogs.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Meanwhile, Alden and his men had waited in their boat a short distance from the shore, however their men were becoming agitated.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The tide was coming in and Alden didn't trust the natives as much as Underwood did.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A messenger soon came from Underwood giving him an update of the situation.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden sent a message to Underwood to stop negotiating and return to the ship.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He sent Wilkes' Nephew Midshipman Wilkes Henry (who was named after his Uncle), to deliver the message.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Soon after, a Canoe came up alongside the *Leopard* and began talking to the chief's son.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Fijian attempted to get out of the boat, but Aden pulled him down.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another half an hour passed, and negotiations seemed to be progressing.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Another messenger from Underwood informed Alden that the chief wanted a hatchet and then the hogs would go to the sailors.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden gave the man the hatchet and he ran to give it to Underwood.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Not long after Emmons arrived in one of the cutters.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He and his crew had been looking for an area to eat the pigs at the nearby Malolo Lailai island, and began discussing it with Alden.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was sharing with Emmons his anxieties over the negotiations and the chief's son's attempted escape, when the native leaped out of the boat and made for the opposite direction from the village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered one of his men to shoot over the chief's head to entice him to return.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Accounts differ as to what happened next, however when the shot went off.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden and Emmons claimed that the chief's son's escape attempt was a signal for the natives to attack.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While those who were negotiating with the chief claimed that the attack began after the shot was fired.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Either way, the chief shouted that he thought that the sailors on the beach had killed his son, and ordered an assault.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Two Fijians grabbed the musket of one of Underwood's men, named Joseph Clark.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark gripped the musket and then brandished a knife.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He stabbed one native and then bashed another with the muskets' shoulder stock.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, several natives began spilling out of the mangrove bushes.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's men began to fire their muskets as they retreated to the two boats.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] About 100 natives began to give chase to the men retreating on the beach and threw spears and throwing clubs at their enemy.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes Henry and Underwood covered the retreat.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry was hit by a club and then shot the man who threw it at him.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then another native hit him in the back of the head.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Henry collapsed to the ground with his face in the water, was surrounded by natives, and then stripped.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Joseph Clark was hit by a glancing blow in the mouth and the spear landed in Underwood's left arm.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark shot the man who threw the spear in the head and then another native knocked Clark out with a club.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He fell into the water, but the pain from the salt water on his bloody face soon woke him.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark stood up and witnessed Underwood being clubbed in the back of the head.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark attempted to drag Underwood to safety with one arm, and hit away other natives with his other.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Clark was hit twice more and fell down.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got back up when he noticed another native was about to club the unconscious Underwood and stabbed him repeatedly.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark grabbed Underwood again who briefly came to and told him to tell his wife he loved her.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Underwood had his head clubbed in and died.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark was left in a state of shock and delirium.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He got up and limped to the rest of the escaping sailors.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Clark's face was covered in blood and dangling flesh and in his absent minded state, he laughed and sang at the natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives were perplexed by Clark's actions and stayed clear of him for the rest of the engagement.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Besides Clark, all the men who retreated back to the beach that survived suffered injuries.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Aldan and Emmons saw the fighting on the beach their crews began to row for the shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the other retreating men had assembled at the boats with Alden and Emmons, Alden a handful of men went back to look for Underwood and Henry.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They encountered Clark in his delusional state and sent him back to the boats.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had retreated back to their village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then Alden and his men found the bodies of both of Underwood and Henry almost completely naked.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Underwood's face was smashed beyond recognition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As for Henry, aside from the bruising and his nudity, Henry looked unharmed, but his mourners soon realized that Henry had drowned while unconscious.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the beach, there lay the bodies of ten Fijians from the attack.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of them stirred and was still alive, and in a fit of fury and vengeance the men, shot and stabbed him several times, before cutting off his head.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of the men, wanted to pursue the natives back to their village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] But there were less than two dozen men, and the natives could return at any moment and overwhelm them.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden commanded the men make a swift retreat back to the rest of the expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The bodies of Henry and Underwood were gingerly placed in the cutter and covered in jackets to uphold their dignity, and the two boats sailed back to the *Flying Fish*.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once the bodies were brought on board they were placed in the ships port side and covered with a tarp.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The cadavers were stitched into hammocks, draped in flags, buried on a nearby small island, and hidden out of fear that the natives would dig up and cannibalize the bodies.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes named the Island Henry Island after his Nephew (not to be confused with Henry Island (Washington), which he also named after his Nephew later in the expedition).
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That night (July 24) Wilkes set up boat patrols commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Eld around Malolo to ensure no native escaped.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It became evident that the natives also expected a counterattack.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fijians in full war paint and equipped with muskets were scattered around the shoreline and would fire pot shots at the boat crews.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The crews would occasionally fire back, but the natives would take cover and drop prone before a musket ball could hit them.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes sent a force of about 70 men and a Fijian scout in 3 divisions.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The force was commanded by Lieutenant Ringgold, they landed in Southern Malolo.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave orders to kill all men and burn the village, but "spare only the women and the children.".
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From there the men began marching to the fortified village of Sualib just outside of where Underwood and Henry were killed.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* waited on the coast with their cannons fixed on the shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The *Flying Fish* was originally going to lead the boats into battle, but it grounded on a sandbar.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the meantime Wilkes organized a small fleet of boats commanded by Alden, Emmons, and Clark whose mission was to search and destroy all hostile escaping canoes.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] There other objective was to approach the smaller Arro (sometimes called Yaro) village and neutralize it while Ringgold's force would destroy Sualib and link up with Wilkes flotilla in Arro.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As the landing party was disembarking, three canoes appeared and were headed to Malolo Lailai.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and Alden took two boats and pursued them.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Once they were close enough an interpreter asked the natives where they were from.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native responded that they were from Malolo.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed six natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The rest of the natives jumped in the water.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden ordered that the rest be taken as prisoners, but his men had bloodlust and shouted "Kill" repeatedly.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One man grabbed a Fijian woman by the hair and was about to slash her with his sword when Alden aimed his pistol at him.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Alden was able to reign in his men and together with Emmons, and they captured several men, women, and children, including a chief from Arro village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men were handcuffed and kept captive, but the women and children were released on the beach.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While Emmons and Alden were occupied capturing the natives during their engagement, Wilkes proceeded with his boats to Arro.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He found the village deserted, and put it to the flame.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The men had gone ahead to join the defense of Sualib and the women and children had fled to the mountains.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes continued on and hoped to reinforce Ringgold at Sualib, but found it destroyed.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He doubled back and later met Ringgold at Arro.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ground force landed at 10 A.M. and divided up in to three groups as Wilkes had ordered.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The groups were led by Lieutenants Ringgold, Robert Johnson and Andrew Murray, and included passed midshipman Henry Eld and Alfred Thomas Agate of the science corps.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ringgold gave a short speech and reminded the men to destroy everything except the women and children.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The forces split up into different paths and destroyed farms along the way, before meeting up and surrounded the fort.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort itself was circular, with a 12 foot wide by 6 feet deep ditch/dry moat which they used as a trench, and a ten foot tall coconut tree and whicker palisade on all sides.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives had occupied the trench and the palisade edges, and together they either aimed their muskets outside of the trench through small holes in the palisade walls.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A number of chiefs, recognizable by their white headdresses, commanded the warriors in between the trenches and stockade.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The warriors began to shout obscenities at the oncoming attackers.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans fired a Congreve rocket and their muskets at the fort, and the Fijians quickly dashed into the fort.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The enemy retreated, a portion of Johnson's division, without orders stormed the fort.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The attack was spearheaded by Sinclair with a double barrel shotgun.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] When Sinclair entered the fort he quickly realized that it was a trap.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The ditch which had been built outside of the palisades also extended into the interior and was occupied by a large number of natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This included women armed with bows who fought with their men.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Retreat for Sinclair and his advance was impractical and decidedly more dangerous than it was worth.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fort was purposefully built like a fish weir trap, with a wide opening, but a narrow avenue of escape.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair got shot with an arrow in his lapel, but it only penetrated the fabric of his coat and not the skin.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Sinclair's fortune did not stop at his lapel.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans began running up to the palisade and shooting into the village through the small holes the Fijians had previously been using.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Musket fire and Congreve rockets poured into Sualib.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Americans began trickling into the village, in twos, by a narrow bridge, through the gate, and into the fort following Sinclair's example.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At one point Sinclair shot a chief with his pistol, which turned out to be the chief of Sualib.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Several natives carried the chiefs limp body to a nearby hut.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The battle crept on in a state of havoc for about 15–30 minutes before a Congreve rocket hit the top of a dry roof and caught fire.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A native warrior got on to of the roof in an effort to remove the rocket before the fire spread, but he was shot down in a hail of bullets.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The fire proliferated and began to engulf the village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The blaze forced the natives to flee the ditch and into American musket fire, which cut them down.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The resulting spectacle was pure pandemonium.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] A translator attempted to shout that the women and children would be allowed to escape.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Fire and gun smoke were everywhere, children were weeping, pigs were crying, the fire roared, the noise was ear splitting.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans cheered their success and then fell back to a coconut grove, as the village burned.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After a half an hour to an hour, the fires had settled to an approachable state, the Americans reentered the village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They soon discovered, that based on the remaining native supplies, the natives had expected a lengthy engagement.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The Americans found piles of hollowed out calabashes filled with water, burnt yams and charred pigs.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Discarded muskets, spears, and clubs littered the floor of the ditch.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The weapons were pilled up on a pyre and immolated.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After searching the still standing huts, Underwood's bloody cap was discovered.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Out of the bodies only four or five survived being burnt to ashes including a little girl and the chief of Sualib.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The preservation of the chief's cadaver was soon ended, as with a streak of vengeance, the Americans threw his body into a burning house.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Evidence of the horror that had occurred before was still present to the senses of the Americans.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The treeline was pierced by misfired arrows.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The smoke filled the nostrils of the sailors and marines which took on the smell of burnt human flesh, as it approached the heavens in an otherwise blue sky.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was in this setting that the otherwise exhausted combatants decided to rest and refresh themselves on coconuts to quench their thirst.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] While the men drank, it was discovered that the most significant injury among them was a sailor who suffered a solitary gash on the leg from an arrow.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After the brief respite, the force divided into the marching lines to the nearby village of Arro and burned several houses and farms along the way.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] It was suspected that most of the surviving villagers were hiding somewhere in the hills.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, they did encounter one native on the way who was instantly bayonetted multiple times to death.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Upon arriving there, they found that Arro had already been burned down by Wilkes and Alden.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Adding the bayoneted man as a casualty and counting the lowest and highest estimate, approximately 58 to about 88 Fijians had been killed between Arro and Sualib.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The last skirmish that occurred during the battle lasted throughout much of the day.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After midday, Lieutenant Emmons had been tracking five canoes that had been spotted in the morning.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] They had escaped Malolo, and were hiding near Malolo Lailai.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Each canoe contained about eight fighters and their sides were reinforced to curb a potential attack.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons was sailing his cutter which was, at this point, only at half its normal capacity.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He had only seven men under his command.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In any case, Emmons made full sail and pulled up alongside the closest canoe.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons fired the forward mounted blunderbuss and killed several natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons and another sailor jumped in the canoe, as Emmons grappled with a spear throwing native, the sailor killed him with a hatchet.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One canoe got away, but the natives in the other canoes jumped overboard.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] After they took the plunge, they were either shot, slashed, or axed by the Americans as they swam for the shallows.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Emmons sailed back to the *Porpoise* before midnight.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In the morning it was discovered that the bodies of the natives killed by Emmons and his men were eaten by sharks.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The next day (July 25, 1840) Wilkes made plans with a declaration to lead a second engagement to kill "Every man on the Island", however an assembly of natives congregated on the beach near the *Flying Fish*.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes summoned an interpreter and together they sailed on a gig to shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] As Wilkes drew nearer the crowd dispersed, leaving behind a lone native woman to treat with Wilkes.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The native offered Wilkes some of Underwood and Henry's clothes, belongings, and a chicken as an offer of peace.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes retrieved the recovered items from his fallen crewmen, but refused the chicken.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes was under the impression that according to Fijian tradition, for a nation to be truly conquered the populace of that nation must be present to witness a peace declaration.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Instead Wilkes entreated to the woman, he and his men would meet on a hill in southern Malolo to discuss peace terms with the whole tribe.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] If however, the remaining chiefs and peoples of Malolo did not make an appearance, then Wilkes and his men would continue the onslaught.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Around noon, Wilkes and his men climbed the hill, which perfectly overlooked views of the sheer destruction yesterday had delivered.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Then, at approximately 4 P.M. a column of weeping natives (including 40 men) began to approach the hill.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] At first, the native would not go beyond the foot of the hill.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes threatened to wipe them out if they did not climb the hill in an act of contrite submission.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] The natives crawled on their hands and knees up the hill.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] An old native man approached Wilkes, spoke for Malolo.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He begged for mercy, and declared that his people would never attack white men again.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He admitted his people were conquered and had only about 80 surviving men left.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] He also offered Wilkes two young native women in reparation.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes gave a speech through a translator about the power of "white" people and that if a similar attack ever happened again, then he would drive the people of Malolo to extinction.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] July 26, Wilkes and his men went to what was left of Arro village and had the people fill casks of water for his vessels.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On the morning of July 27, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* sailed off the coast of Arro and 70 natives loaded them with 3,000 gallons of water, 12 pigs, and 3,000 coconuts.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] That same day the natives retrieved Underwood's pocket watch which had melted in the fire, and Henry's glasses.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] On July 31, the *Flying Fish* and *Porpoise* returned to Bua bay where the rest of the fleet was working.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes privately blamed Alden and Underwood for the deaths of Henry and Underwood.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] In retaliation Wilkes had Underwood's possessions sold at an auction to much protest from the officers, and most notably midshipman James Blair who was the executor of Underwood's freshly written will just prior to the battle of Malolo.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes vindictive streak did not appear to end with Underwood.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes next turned his anger to chief Veidovi.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] From his capture up until the end of the expedition in Fiji, Hudson had been kind to Veidovi and even permitted him to go on deck and speak to the officers.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] However, Wilkes had Veidovi transferred from the *Peacock* to his flagship the *Vincennes*.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Now Wilkes kept Veidovi confined to quarters.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Moreover, Wilkes had the ships barber cut Vincennes hair.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] This mortified Veidovi, since his hair marked his status and was important in Fijian culture.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Ex. had ended Wilkes published a book called *Narrative of the United States Exploring Expedition* in 1844.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] Wilkes in hindsight was mad at Alden for a number of perceived grievances.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] One of these grievances included the idea that Alden was responsible for the deaths of Underwood and Henry.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p01] And he wrote about this an his other grievances in his book.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. left Fiji in August and set a course for more surveying and scientific work in Hawaii, before temporary splitting up the expedition to survey Hawaii and other islands in Polynesia such as modern day French Polynesia, the Cook Islands, and the Gilbert Islands.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, the expedition surveyed the Columbia River.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] On the return trip the expedition traveled to Wake Island, and returned by way of the Philippines, Borneo, Singapore, Polynesia, and the Cape of Good Hope, reaching New York on June 10, 1842.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While on the surveying expedition for the Columbia river, Wilkes appeared to have loosened his enmity to Veidovi at one point.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He began allowing him on the deck of the *Vincennes*.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] A few months later on July 4th 1841 Wilkes and his men landed on Vancouver Island and fired off two howitzers in celebration of the holiday.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] During this occasion Veidovi was allowed to walk on shore.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The next year in June, 4th 1842 Veidovi died a few days after landing in New York (possibly from pulmonary tuberculosis), although the Washington Herald inaccurately asserted that Veidovi died from a lack of eating human meat.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Veidovi's death surgeons at the Brooklyn Naval Hospital removed Veidovi's head, pickled it, and then after a time the flesh was removed, and the skull was thereafter labeled Specimen 292 and was featured in the Smithsonian Institution, and became one of the most popular exhibits.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Soon after Wilkes' arrival in New York several court martials were organized for the entire Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes had made many enemies in both the Navy, and the government.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He was almost universally despised by his men for many of the actions he took during the expedition.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Other officers were charged with various crimes, but Wilkes was charged with 11, and his actions throughout the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. were criticized in the defense of the other officers.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his actions during Fiji the Battle of Malolo, Wilkes was charged with illegally attacking the natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes justified his actions by stating "But I felt then as I do now, that the punishment was sufficient and effectual, while it was accompanied, as far as it could be, with mercy.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, even the most ardent of Wilkes detractors supported Wilkes on this matter.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Many of them indicated by their words and actions that they hated the natives for killing their friends and desired revenge.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] What's more, Wilkes was able to garner sympathy for the death of his nephew of which it was universally acknowledged that he loved dearly.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ultimately Wilkes was cleared of all charges including his Fiji charges.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The exception was that Wilkes was found guilty of illegally flogging marines and sailors in Hawaii after they refused to work when their enlistments were up.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As a consequence, Wilkes was given a public reprimand.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In 1843, a 22-foot cenotaph obelisk was built in Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge Massachusetts to remember the officers who had fallen in the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] More specifically, the monument memorialized the loss of life in two separate events of the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This included the loss of the USS *Sea Gull* (1838) a schooner that was Captained by Midshipman James W.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Reid with the help of Midshipman Frederick A.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The *Sea Gull* was awaiting resupply from the USS *Relief* (1836), after which she was due to rendezvous with the rest of the fleet at Valparaíso, Chile.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] She was last spotted off Cape Horn at Midnight on 28 April 1839.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] After a while when the *Sea Gull* never returned the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] While one side of the obelisk commemorates the memory of the officers of the *Sea Gull*, another preserves the memory of Henry Wilkes and Joseph Underwood killed during the first day of the battle of Malolo.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Officers and Scientific Corps. of the expedition took up a collection for their fallen comrades by the end of the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes and his family desired that this monument should be constructed at a cemetery in Brooklyn, New York for the benefit of Henry's mother and sister who lived near by.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, in part due to spite over Wilkes' treatment of them the officers had the monument built in Cambridge close to Underwood's widow.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Specifically the Obelisk reads: "To the memory of Lieutenant Joseph A.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Underwood and Midshipman Wilkes Henry, U.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This cenotaph is erected by their associates, the officers and scientific corps of the U.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Methodist missionary Reverend David Cargill reported to Hudson that because of the arrest of Veidovi, the other chiefs of Rewa became terrified at the prospect of harming white people.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And that this show of strength served to aid in both Western trade and missionary work.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] For his political, translation, and informative aid in the expedition Wilkes made David Whippey the temporary consul of the United States in Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Later, a more formal consul named John B.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, with Wilkes' recommendation Secretary of State John C.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Calhoun appointed him to vice consul of Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Nancy Shoemaker, she theorizes the combination of the Fijians newfound fear of retribution for attacks against Westerners following the attacks of the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.. combined with Whippey's new position of power provided a lasting impact on Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In that vein of thought, Shoemaker points out that Whippey's new found power complemented his unofficial title as chief of the white men/beachcombers of Levuka and the Royal Messenger of Bau village.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] With this fusion of power came a desire for autonomy for both Whippey and the white beachcombers he represented.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Traditionally, the beachcombers were compelled to fight for whichever local chief had them under employment.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, when chief Cakobau of Bau called them up to aid in him waging war against Cakaudrove at Somosomo, the beachcombers refused.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] They claimed they wished to protect their property.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Cakobau became incensed, and was even more so after he lost the war against Cakaudrove.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He feared that directly punishing Whippey and his beachcombers might bring down the wrath of the United States or another western power.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Instead his punishment of the beachcombers was indirect and subtle.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He encouraged other tribes under his domain to steal the beachcombers polygamous wives.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He later demanded greater tributes from them and sent arsonists to burn down their homes.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The situation became exasperated when in 1843, the beachcombers refused to participate in the Bau–Rewa war.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] This time Cakobau exiled the whites and their mixed-race children to Bua and near the village of Solevu that was destroyed by the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, by 1849, Cakobau allowed the beachcombers to return to Levuka.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Trade in Levuka had suffered since the exile.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers were all to often, the most reliable middlemen traders for Fijians and the trade ships that came through Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] To Cakobau's dismay upon the beachcombers return they began to dominate all foreign trade to the exclusion of Cakobau and the Fijian people as a whole.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers under Whippey began defending themselves against small skirmishes or arsons as advanced by Cakobau.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] At this point beachcombers like Whippey, and their mixed families, had begun to transcend from being middleman minorities to autonomous settlers.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The beachcombers at Levuka and elsewhere gradually made moves to separate themselves from the Fijian populace and became a semi independent military and trading power.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The British would later capitalize upon this development, when they took ownership of it in 1874 and made Levuka its first capital.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] However, according to Shoemaker, it was the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex.'s precedent for protection and subsequent retaliation for harm against whites that began the beachcombers move towards autonomy and the later British take over of the islands.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. taken as a whole led to several lasting scientific revelations, explorative discoveries, and historical preservations that continue to endure to today.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji expeditions artifacts contributed to the earliest collections for the National Institute for the Promotion of Science, the precursor to what would become the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] In addition to the cannibalized skull and the skull of chief Veidovi, an assortment of Fijian weapons had been procured for future display at the institute.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Wilkes names the Ringgold Isles after Lieutenant Cadwalader Ringgold.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Numerous botanical samples were also obtained from Fiji and other lands the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. surveyed, and were placed in the United States Botanic Garden or the Smithsonian Gardens.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Dried plant specimens comprised the core of what is now the **National Herbarium**, an herbarium curated by the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of Natural History.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] The Fiji Expedition was also not without its merits, for its contributions to science.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] As mentioned previously, Horatio Hale documented 5,600 words in the Fiji language as well as other information of anthological and cultural importance.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Through his studies he produced the book *Ethnography and Philology* (1846), which is said to have laid the foundations of the ethnography of Polynesia, including Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] He is often cited as the Father of Polynesian ethnology.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Moreover, the scientists Charles Pickering, William Brackenridge, and William Rich, collectively brought over 50,000 specimens of 10,000 species.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] And of the 241 charts that were created during the Ex.
[src:american-civil-war/1840-fiji-expedition-p02] Ex. there was included the first ever complete chart of Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] In October 1855, the United States Navy sent a warship to Fiji during the civil war on the islands.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] They demanded compensation from Seru Epenisa Cakobau, the Vunivalu of Bau and self-proclaimed Tui Viti (King of Fiji), in response to the alleged arson attacks on the American commercial agent in Lautoka, Viti Levu.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] The initial incident that led to the American expedition was the burning in 1849 of the house owned by agent John Brown Williams when it was hit by cannon fire.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] A subsequent incident happened the same year as the expedition when, again, fire was to interrupt Williams's duties.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Another accidental fire on Nukulau destroyed his store, and some Fijians looted it.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Boutwell, was sent to monitor the unrest in October, and her crew landed multiple times to protect American interests.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] When Commander Boutwell heard of the incidents involving William's house and store, he demanded US$5,000 in compensation from King Cakobau.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] This initial claim was supplemented by further claims totalling $45,000.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] He gave the natives a deadline and threatened them with a landing party of marines and sailors to capture the king in the island's village if they failed to pay.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Fijian warriors put up some resistance, one American service man was killed, and two were wounded.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Ultimately the Adams's men were successful in routing a contingent of natives from Lautoka, but Cakobau and the survivors escaped capture.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] Cakobau's claim to be King of Fiji was by no means universally recognised by his fellow-chiefs who jealously guarded the independence of their fiefdoms.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] If he acknowledged the debt, he did not have sufficient funds to pay it, yet if he disclaimed it by saying that it fell under the jurisdiction of another chief, he would jeopardize his claim to the kingship, which he wanted foreign powers to recognise.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] He decided to bide his time, hoping that the Americans were only bluffing.
[src:american-civil-war/1855-fiji-expedition] An 1858 Fiji expedition, involving the crew of *Vandalia*, achieved clearer results, and the debt itself was not resolved until 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] In 1858, the United States Navy launched an operation on the island of Waya in Fiji following the death of two American traders there.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The Pacific Squadron executed a punitive expedition against the native warriors of Seru Epenisa Cakobau and defeated them in a pitched battle at the village of Somatti.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] In mid-1858, two American citizens on Waya were killed and cannibalized by the natives.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] When word of the incident reached the American consulate at Ovalau, the Pacific Squadron sent the *Vandalia*, and the sloop-of-war arrived on 2 October 1858.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The *Vandalia'*s draft was not shallow enough to reach Waya, so Commander Sinclair chartered the schooner *Mechanic* and placed her under the command of veteran Lieutenant Charles Caldwell.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] A force of 10 marines, forty sailors and a 12-pounder howitzer were mustered for the landing on Waya.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] A few Fijian guides and three American merchant sailors also participated.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] One was Captain Josiah Knowles of the *Wild Wave*, a clipper ship wrecked off Oeno Island.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Knowles and 40 others were marooned on the island until being rescued by *Vandalia* and taken to Fiji.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The expedition left Ovalau on 6 October 1858 and sailed west around the northern end of the main island of Viti Levu to Waya.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] During their passage to the island, Lieutenant Caldwell's men heard many stories from towns and villages about the warriors of Waya.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The Wayan chiefs responsible for the deaths of the two American traders also sent a letter: "Do you suppose we have killed the two white men for nothing?
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] No, we killed them and we have eaten them.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] We are great warriors, and we delight in war".
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell later wrote, "...and woe to the members of any strange tribe that falls into their hands... to be clubbed to death and eaten is the only alternative for the captive.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] It is not a matter of surprise that the tribes along our route learned with feelings of satisfaction the nature of our expedition".
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] At 03:00 on 9 October, the Americans made a landing and marched inland toward the village of Somatti over tropical and mountainous terrain.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] While climbing through the mountains, the 12-pounder was destroyed and left behind when it fell 2,300 feet (700 m) down the side of a hill as the expedition tried to pull it up.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The column reached Somatti in daytime, and over 300 native warriors were in front of the village for defense, clothed in white robes and armed with clubs, rocks, spears, bows, and some muskets.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The Americans had swords and carbine rifles.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Lieutenant Caldwell ordered a flanking maneuver on the left side of the mass of warriors.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Routed, the natives dispersed themselves amongst the town or fled into the jungle.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Bartlett, who led a group of sailors, sang "Red, White, and Blue" and let out three cheers before charging and capturing the village.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The crew of the 12-pounder, with no gun to fire, took charge of burning the village, and over 115 huts were destroyed.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Marines under Lieutenant Alan Ramsey, providing a rearguard for the sailors, repulsed a final Wayan attack from the jungle after they had regrouped.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] In all fourteen warriors, including the two chiefs, were counted dead after a fierce half-hour battle.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Two marines survived their wounds by musketry, two sailors were hurt badly by rocks, one other marine was hit in the leg with an arrow, and a sailor from *Wild Wave* was hurt as well.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] After the battle the Americans took until 16 October to return to the coast where the *Mechanic* was waiting.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] They stopped at friendly Fijian fishing villages and spread the news of their victory.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] Caldwell noted that two ramrods and one bayonet were lost during the march, and a large amount of ammunition was used in battle.
[src:american-civil-war/1858-fiji-expedition] The lieutenant received much credit for the operation, considered one of the most impressive military campaigns launched by the United States in the South Pacific during the nineteenth century.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] A United States presidential election was held on November 6, 1860.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Republican Party ticket of Abraham Lincoln and Hannibal Hamlin emerged victorious.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In 1860, the United States was divided over the issue of slavery, and four major political parties had nominated candidates in the 1860 presidential election.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent president James Buchanan, a Democrat, did not seek re-election.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The anti-slavery Republican Party nominated Abraham Lincoln, who previously had been a one-term Whig Representative from Illinois, for president.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Its platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states where it existed, but opposed its extension into the territories.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party, which sought to avoid disunion by resolving divisions over slavery with some new compromise.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Constitutional Union Convention put forward former Tennessee Senator John Bell for president.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] After the 1860 Democratic National Convention adjourned without agreeing on a nominee, a second convention nominated Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas as the Northern Democratic presidential candidate.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas's support for the concept of popular sovereignty, which called for each territory's settlers to decide the status of slavery within the territory, alienated many radical pro-slavery Southern Democrats.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] With President Buchanan's support, Southern Democrats held their own convention, nominating Vice President John C.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a majority in the Electoral College, with all his Electoral College votes coming from Northern states.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He prevailed in 18 states, won 180 electoral votes, and received 39.7 percent of the popular vote.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas won the second-highest popular vote total, but won only the state of Missouri; he was the only candidate in the 1860 election to win electoral votes in both free and slave states.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge won 11 states, finishing third in the popular vote, while Bell finished fourth in the popular vote and won the electoral votes of the states of Kentucky, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In the last presidential election in which it appointed its presidential electors at the discretion of the state legislature rather than by popular vote (and was the only state to do so), the presidential electors of South Carolina cast their ballots for Breckinridge.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 election was the first of six consecutive Republican presidential victories.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's election as the first Republican president served as the main catalyst for Southern secession and the American Civil War.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] His election motivated seven Southern states, all of which had voted for Breckinridge, to secede from the United States before Lincoln's inauguration on March 4, 1861.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Civil War began less than two months after the inauguration with the Battle of Fort Sumter, after which four more slave states seceded.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 presidential election conventions were unusually tumultuous, particularly because a split in the Democratic Party had led to both Northern and Southern party conventions.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Republican National Convention met in mid-May 1860 after the Democrats had been forced to adjourn their convention in Charleston.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] With the Democrats in disarray and a sweep of the Northern states possible, the Republicans felt confident going into their convention in Chicago.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Seward from New York was considered the front-runner, followed by Salmon P.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Chase from Ohio, and Missouri's Edward Bates.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Abraham Lincoln from Illinois was less well-known and was not considered to have a good chance against Seward.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been governor and senator of New York, and was an able politician with a Whig background.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Clay, and Benjamin Wade, who might be able to win if the convention deadlocked.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] As the convention developed, however, it was revealed that frontrunners Seward, Chase, and Bates had each alienated factions of the Republican Party.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Seward had been painted as a radical, and his speeches on slavery predicted inevitable conflict, which spooked moderate delegates.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He also was firmly opposed to nativism, which further weakened his position.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He had also been abandoned by his longtime friend and political ally Horace Greeley, publisher of the influential *New-York Tribune*.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Chase, a former Democrat, had alienated many of the former Whigs by his coalition with the Democrats in the late 1840s.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He had also opposed tariffs demanded by Pennsylvania and even had opposition from his own delegation from Ohio.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Chase's firm anti-slavery stance made him popular with the Radical Republicans; but what he offered in policy, he lacked in charisma and political acumen.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The conservative Bates was an unlikely candidate but found support from Horace Greeley, who sought any chance to defeat Seward, with whom he now had a bitter feud.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He was not unknown; he had gained prominence in the 1858 Lincoln–Douglas debates and had represented Illinois in the House of Representatives.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln had been quietly eyeing a run since the debates, ensuring that they were widely published and that a biography of himself was published.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He gained great renown with his acclaimed February 1860 Cooper Union speech, which may have ensured him the nomination, even though he had not yet announced his intention to run.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Delivered in Seward's home state and attended by Greeley, Lincoln used the speech to show that the Republican Party was a party of moderates, not crazed fanatics, as Southerners and Democrats claimed.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Afterward, Lincoln was in much demand for speaking engagements.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] As the convention approached, Lincoln did not campaign actively, as the "office was expected to seek the man".
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] So it did at the Illinois state convention, a week before the national convention.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Young politician Richard Oglesby found several fence rails that Lincoln may have split as a youngster and paraded them into the convention with a banner that proclaimed Lincoln to be "The Rail Candidate" for president.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received a thunderous ovation, surpassing his and his political allies' expectations.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's campaign managers had printed and distributed thousands of fake convention admission tickets to Lincoln supporters to ensure and increase the crowd's support.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Even with such support from his home state, Lincoln faced a difficult task if he was to win the nomination.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He set about ensuring that he was the second choice of most delegates, realizing that the first round of voting at the convention was unlikely to produce a clear winner.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He engineered that the convention would be held in Chicago, which would be inherently friendly to the Illinois-based Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He also made sure that the Illinois delegation would vote as a bloc for him.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln did not attend the convention in person and left the task of delegate wrangling to several close friends.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The first round of voting predictably produced a lead for Seward, but not a majority, with Lincoln in second place.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The second round eliminated most of the minor contenders, with voters switching mostly to Seward or Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The convention remained deadlocked, however, and successful political maneuvering by Lincoln's delegates persuaded some delegates to abandon Seward in favor of Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's combination of a moderate stance on slavery, his position on economic issues, his western origins, and his strong oratory proved to be exactly what the delegates wanted in a president.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] On the third ballot on May 18, Lincoln secured the presidential nomination overwhelmingly.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Senator Hannibal Hamlin from Maine was nominated for vice president, defeating Clay.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The party platform promised not to interfere with slavery in the states, but opposed slavery in the territories.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The platform promised tariffs protecting industry and workers, a Homestead Act granting free farmland in the West to settlers, and the funding of a transcontinental railroad.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] There was no mention of Mormonism (which had been condemned in the Party's 1856 platform), the Fugitive Slave Act, personal liberty laws, or the Dred Scott decision.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] While the Seward forces were disappointed at the nomination of a little-known western upstart, they rallied behind Lincoln, while abolitionists were angry at the selection of a moderate and had little faith in Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas from Illinois, James Guthrie from Kentucky, Robert Mercer Taliaferro Hunter from Virginia, Joseph Lane from Oregon, Daniel S.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Dickinson from New York, and Andrew Johnson from Tennessee, while three other candidates, Isaac Toucey from Connecticut, James Pearce from Maryland, and Jefferson Davis from Mississippi (the future president of the Confederate States) also received votes.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, a moderate on the slavery issue who favored "popular sovereignty", was ahead on the first ballot, but was 56½ votes short of securing the nomination.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] On the 57th ballot, with Douglas still ahead, but 51½ votes short of the nomination, the exhausted and desperate delegates agreed on May 3 to cease voting and adjourn the convention.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] While some considered Horatio Seymour a compromise candidate for the national Democratic nomination at the reconvening convention in Baltimore, Seymour wrote a letter to the editor of his local newspaper declaring unreservedly that he was not a candidate for either spot on the ticket.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] After two ballots - the 59th ballot overall - the remaining Democrats nominated Stephen A.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The election would now pit Lincoln against his longtime political rival, whom Lincoln had lost to in the Illinois senate race just two years earlier.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] That two candidates were from Illinois showed the importance of the West in the election.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] While Benjamin Fitzpatrick from Alabama was nominated for vice president, he refused the nomination.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] After the convention concluded with no vice presidential nominee, Douglas offered the vice presidential nomination to Herschel V.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The southern delegates walked out of Institute Hall on April 30, moving at first to the Saint Andrews Hall, then to Military Hall on May 1st.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] On May 3rd, when the northern delegates left Charleston, the southern delegates left as well, reconvening at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, Virginia on June 11.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] When the Democrats reconvened at Front Street Theater in Baltimore, they rejoined (except South Carolina and Florida, who had stayed in Richmond).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] When the convention seated two replacement delegations on June 18, they walked out again or boycotted the convention, accompanied by nearly all other Southern delegates and erstwhile Convention chair Caleb Cushing, a New Englander and former member of Franklin Pierce's cabinet.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] This larger group met immediately in Baltimore's Maryland Institute Hall, with Cushing again presiding.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] They adopted the pro-slavery platform rejected at Charleston, and nominated Vice President John C.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge for president, and Senator Joseph Lane from Oregon for vice president.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Yancey and some (less than half) of the bolters - almost entirely from the Lower South - met on June 28 at Metropolitan Hall in Richmond, along with the South Carolina and Florida delegations, at a convention that affirmed the nominations of Breckinridge and Lane.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Besides the Democratic parties in the Southern states, the Breckinridge/Lane ticket was also supported by the Buchanan administration.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Buchanan's own continued prestige in his home state of Pennsylvania ensured that Breckinridge would be the principal Democratic candidate in that populous state.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge was the last sitting vice president nominated for president until Richard Nixon in 1960.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Constitutional Union Party was formed by remnants of both the defunct Know Nothing and Whig parties who were unwilling to join either the Republicans or the Democrats.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The new party's members hoped to stave off Southern secession by avoiding the slavery issue.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] They met in the Eastside District Courthouse of Baltimore and nominated John Bell from Tennessee for president over Governor Sam Houston of Texas on the second ballot.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett was nominated for vice president at the convention on May 9, 1860, one week before Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] John Bell was a former Whig who had opposed the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the Lecompton Constitution.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Edward Everett had been president of Harvard University and Secretary of State in the Millard Fillmore administration.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Radical Abolitionist Party was a remnant of the Liberty Party that formed after most former Liberty and Free Soil Party members joined the Republicans in the 1850s.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] A convention of one hundred delegates was held in Convention Hall, Syracuse, New York, on August 29, 1860.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Delegates were in attendance from New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Michigan, Illinois, Ohio, Kentucky, and Massachusetts.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Gerrit Smith, a prominent abolitionist and the 1848 presidential nominee of the original Liberty Party, had sent a letter in which he stated that his health had been so poor that he had not been able to be away from home since 1858.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, he remained popular in the party because he had helped inspire some of John Brown's supporters at the Raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In his letter, Smith donated $50 to pay for the printing of ballots in the various states.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] There was quite a spirited contest between the friends of Gerrit Smith and William Goodell in regard to the nomination for the presidency.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In spite of his professed ill health, Gerrit Smith was nominated for president and Samuel McFarland from Pennsylvania was nominated for vice president.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In Ohio, Illinois, and Indiana, slates of presidential electors pledged to Smith and McFarland ran with the name of the Union Party.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] They received a total of 176 votes in the general election, 0.004% of the total.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The People's Party was a loose association of the supporters of Governor Samuel Houston.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] On April 20, 1860, the party held what it termed a national convention to nominate Houston for president on the San Jacinto Battlefield in Texas.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Houston's supporters at the gathering did not nominate a vice presidential candidate, since they expected later gatherings to carry out that function.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Later mass meetings were held in northern cities, such as New York City on May 30, 1860, but they too failed to nominate a vice presidential candidate.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Houston, never enthusiastic about running for the presidency, soon became convinced that he had no chance of winning and that his candidacy would only make it easier for the Republican candidate to win.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He withdrew from the race on August 16, and urged the formation of a Unified "Union" ticket in opposition to Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In their campaigning, Bell and Douglas both claimed that disunion would not necessarily follow a Lincoln election.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Nonetheless, loyal army officers in Virginia, Kansas and South Carolina warned Lincoln of military preparations to the contrary.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Mexican War hero Winfield Scott suggested to Lincoln that he assume the powers of a commander-in-chief before inauguration.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] However, historian Bruce Chadwick observes that Lincoln and his advisors ignored the widespread alarms and threats of secession as mere election trickery.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Indeed, voting in the South was not as monolithic as the Electoral College map would make it seem.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Economically, culturally, and politically, the South was made up of three regions.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In the states of the Upper South, also known as the Border South (Delaware, Maryland, Kentucky, and Missouri), unionist popular votes were scattered among Lincoln, Douglas, and Bell, to form a majority in all four.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In the four Middle South states, there was a unionist majority divided between Douglas and Bell in Virginia and Tennessee; in North Carolina and Arkansas, the unionist (Bell and Douglas) vote approached a majority.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In three of the seven Deep South states, unionists (Bell and Douglas) won divided majorities in Georgia and Louisiana and neared it in Alabama.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge convincingly carried only four of the seven states of the Deep South (South Carolina, Florida, Mississippi, and Texas).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Deep South states had the largest enslaved populations, and consequently the smallest enfranchised free white populations.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Among the slave states, the three states with the highest voter turnouts voted the most one-sided.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Texas, with five percent of the total wartime South's population, voted 75 percent Breckinridge.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Kentucky and Missouri, with one-fourth of the total population, voted 73 percent pro-Union Bell, Douglas and Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In comparison, the other six states of the Deep South made up one-fourth of the Confederate voting population; this was split 57 percent for Breckinridge versus 43 percent for the two pro-union candidates.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The four states that were admitted to the Confederacy after Fort Sumter held almost half its population, and voted a narrow combined majority of 53 percent for the pro-union candidates.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In the eleven states that would later declare their secession from the Union and be controlled by Confederate armies, ballots for Lincoln were cast only in Virginia, where he received 1,929 votes (1.15 percent of the total).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The vast majority of the votes Lincoln received were cast in border counties of what would soon become West Virginia – the future state accounted for 1,832 of Lincoln's 1,929 votes.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes at all in 121 of the state's at-the-time 145 counties (including 31 of the 50 that would form West Virginia), received a single vote in three counties and received ten or fewer votes in nine of the 24 counties where he polled votes.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Hancock County (Virginia's northernmost at the time) returned Lincoln's best result – he polled over 40% of the vote there and finished in second place (Lincoln polled only eight votes fewer than Breckinridge).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Of the 97 votes cast for Lincoln in the state's post-1863 boundaries, 93 were polled in four counties along the Potomac River and four were tallied in the coastal city of Portsmouth.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Although Lincoln received no votes in 10 Southern states, this was not because he was removed from the ballot in those states, but rather due to the Republican Party's absence in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] One key difference between modern elections and those of the mid-nineteenth century is that at the time the state did not print and distribute ballots.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since voters did not choose the president directly, but rather presidential electors, the only way for a voter to meaningfully support a particular candidate for president was cast a ballot for citizens of his state who would have pledged to vote for the candidate in the Electoral College.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In ten southern slave states, no citizen would publicly pledge to vote for Abraham Lincoln, so citizens there had no legal means to vote for the Republican nominee.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In most of Virginia, no publisher would print ballots for Lincoln's pledged electors.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Of the four slave states that did not secede Lincoln came third in Delaware and fourth in Missouri, Kentucky and Maryland.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Within the fifteen slave states, Lincoln won only two counties out of 996, Missouri's St.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In the 1856 election, the Republican candidate for president had received no votes at all in twelve of the fourteen slave states with a popular vote (these being the same states as in the 1860 election, plus Missouri and Virginia).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The election was held on Tuesday, November 6, 1860, and was noteworthy for the exaggerated sectionalism and voter enthusiasm in a country that was soon to dissolve into civil war.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Voter turnout was 81.2%, the highest in American history up to that time, and the second-highest overall (exceeded only in the election of 1876).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] 31.5% of the voting age population voted.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Since Andrew Jackson had won re-election in 1832, all six subsequent presidents had only won one term, while the last four of those had won with a popular vote under 51 percent.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the Electoral College with less than 40 percent of the popular vote nationwide by carrying states above the Mason–Dixon line and north of the Ohio River, plus the states of California and Oregon in the Far West.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Unlike every preceding president-elect, Lincoln did not carry even one slave state; he instead carried all eighteen free states exclusively.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln received no votes in ten Southern states because the Republican Party was absent in those states (parties rather than states printed ballots in that era).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] There were no ballots distributed for Lincoln in ten of the Southern states: Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] This withheld 61 potential electoral votes from Lincoln, a fifth of what was the total 303 available to the other candidates.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In a similar divide between North and South electors, Breckenridge carried nine of the ten states that withheld Lincoln from the ballot, the exception being Tennessee.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] It should be further noted that, prior to the introduction of the secret ballot in the 1880s, the concept of ballot access did not exist in the sense it does today: there was no standardized state-issued ballot for a candidate to "appear" on.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Instead, presidential ballots were printed and distributed by agents of the candidates and their parties, who organized slates of would-be electors publicly pledged to vote for a particular candidate.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln won the second-lowest share of the popular vote among all winning presidential candidates in U.S. history.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Lincoln's share of the popular vote would likely have been even lower if there had been a popular vote in South Carolina, though conversely it would likely have been marginally higher had Republican ballots been widely available to voters throughout the Southern States.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Republican victory resulted from the concentration of votes in the free states, which together controlled a majority of the presidential electors.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The Wide Awakes young Republican men's organization massively expanded registered voter lists, and population increases in the free states had far exceeded those seen in the slave states for many years before the election of 1860, hence free states dominated in the Electoral College.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Gasconade County, Missouri has voted for a Republican presidential candidate in every election from 1860 on, which, as of 2024, makes it the longest Republican winning streak in presidential elections in the nation.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Despite Lincoln's commanding victory, this was the first election in American history in which the winner failed to win a majority of votes in his home county, with Lincoln narrowly losing Sangamon County, Illinois to Douglas, his main opponent in the North.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Regardless, Lincoln won absolute majorities (>50%) in enough states, that if he lost all states that he took with pluralities, he still would have received enough electoral votes to win.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In short, even if Ranked-Choice Voting, or any other runoff system had been in effect in every state, Lincoln still would have won on the first round.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] In New York, Pennsylvania, and New Jersey, where anti-Lincoln votes were combined into fusion tickets, Lincoln still won New York and Pennsylvania and split New Jersey.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, a shift of 25,000 votes to the fusion ticket in New York would have left Lincoln with 145 electoral votes — seven votes short of winning the Electoral College — and forced a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Alternatively, a shift of only 15,400 votes over California, Illinois, Minnesota, New Jersey, Oregon, and Rhode Island would have left Lincoln short of the necessary 152 electoral votes.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Of the five states that Lincoln failed to carry, he received 20 percent of the vote in only one (Delaware) and 10 percent of the vote in one more (Missouri).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Like Lincoln, Breckinridge and Bell won no electoral votes outside of their respective sections.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] While Bell retired to his family business, quietly supporting his state's secession, Breckinridge served as a Confederate general.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He finished second in the Electoral College with 72 votes, carrying eleven of fifteen slave states (including South Carolina, whose electors were chosen by the state legislature, not popular vote).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge stood a distant third in national popular vote at eighteen percent, but accrued 50 to 75 percent in the first seven states that would form the Confederate States of America.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He took nine of the eleven states that eventually joined, plus the border slave states of Delaware and Maryland, losing only Virginia and Tennessee.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Breckinridge received very little support in the free states, showing some strength only in California, Oregon, Pennsylvania, and Connecticut.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Bell carried three slave states (Tennessee, Kentucky, and Virginia) and lost Maryland by only 722 votes.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, he finished a remarkable second in all slave states won by Breckinridge or Douglas.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] He won 45 to 47 percent in Maryland, Tennessee, and North Carolina and canvassed respectably with 36 to 40 percent in Missouri, Arkansas, Louisiana, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Bell himself had hoped that he would take over the former support of the extinct Whig Party in free states, but the majority of this support went to Lincoln.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Thus, except for running mate Everett's home state of Massachusetts, and California, Bell received even less support in the free states than did Breckinridge, and consequently came in last in the national popular vote, at 12.62%.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas was the only candidate who won electoral votes in both slave and free states (free New Jersey and slave Missouri).
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] His support was the most widespread geographically; he finished second behind Lincoln in the popular vote with 29.52%, but last in the Electoral College.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] His 12 electoral votes are the lowest for a Democrat in history.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas attained a 28 to 47% share in the states of the Mid-Atlantic, Midwest, and Trans-Mississippi West, but slipped to 19 to 39% in New England.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Outside his regional section, Douglas took 15 to 17% of the popular vote total in the slave states of Kentucky, Alabama, and Louisiana, then 10 percent or less in the nine remaining slave states.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Douglas, in his "Norfolk Doctrine", reiterated in North Carolina, promised to keep the Union together by coercion if states proceeded to secede: the popular vote for Lincoln and Douglas combined was 69.17% of the turnout.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] The 1860 Republican ticket was the first successful national ticket that did not feature a Southerner, and the election marked the end of Southern political dominance in the United States.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Between 1789 and 1860, Southerners had been president for two-thirds of the era, and had held the offices of Speaker of the House and President pro tempore of the Senate during much of that time.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] Moreover, since 1791, Southerners had constituted a majority of the Supreme Court.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p01] (b) *The option of Lincoln was absent from 20.13% of ballots across ten states.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln's victory and imminent inauguration as president was the immediate cause for declarations of secession by seven Southern states (South Carolina, Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas) from 20 December 1860 to 1 February 1861.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] They then formed the Confederate States of America.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] On 9 February 1861, Jefferson Davis was elected president of the Confederacy.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] All of the secessionist activity was motivated by fear for the institution of slavery in the South.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] If the President (and, by extension, the appointed federal officials in the South, such as district attorneys, marshals, postmasters, and judges) opposed slavery, it might collapse.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] There were fears that abolitionist agents would infiltrate the South and foment slave insurrections.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] (The noted secessionist William Lowndes Yancey, speaking at New York's Cooper Institute in October 1860, asserted that with abolitionists in power, "Emissaries will percolate between master [and] slave as water between the crevices of rocks underground.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] They will be found everywhere, with strychnine to put in our wells.") Less radical Southerners thought that with Northern antislavery dominance of the federal government, slavery would eventually be abolished, regardless of present constitutional limits.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] Bertram Wyatt-Brown argues that secessionists desired independence as necessary for their honor.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] They could no longer tolerate Northern state attitudes that regarded slave ownership as a great sin and Northern politicians who insisted on stopping the spread of slavery.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] Another bloc of Southerners resented Northern criticism of slavery and restrictions on slavery but opposed secession as dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] However, the "conditional Unionists" also hoped that when faced with secession, Northerners would stifle anti-slavery rhetoric and accept pro-slavery rules for the territories.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] It was that group that prevented immediate secession in Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, and Arkansas when Lincoln took office on March 4, 1861.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] He took no action against the secessionists in the seven "Confederate" states, but also declared that secession had no legal validity and refused to surrender federal property in those states.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] (He also reiterated his opposition to slavery anywhere in the territories.) Preparing to form an army, on 6 March 1861 Davis called for 100,000 volunteers to serve for twelve months.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] The political standoff continued until mid-April, when Davis ordered Confederate troops to bombard and capture Fort Sumter.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] Lincoln then called for troops to put down rebellion, which wiped out the possibility that the crisis could be resolved by compromise.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] Nearly all "conditional Unionists" joined the secessionists, including for example presidential candidate John Bell of the Constitutional Union Party, whose home state of Tennessee was the last to secede.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] The Virginia convention and the reconvened Arkansas convention both declared secession, as did the legislatures of Tennessee and North Carolina; all four states joined the Confederacy.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] Missouri and Kentucky stayed in the United States, but had unrecognized dual governments.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] After the Civil War begun, Douglas then threw his support behind Lincoln and undertook a tour to bolster support for the Union, making visits to Virginia, Ohio and Illinois.
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] Douglas declared "There are no neutrals, only patriots and traitors".
[src:american-civil-war/1860-presidential-election-p02] However, three months after Lincoln's inauguration, Douglas contracted typhoid fever and died in Chicago on June 3, 1861.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The **1862–63 United States House of Representatives elections** were held between June 2, 1862, and November 3, 1863, to elect the 184 members and eight non-voting delegates of the House of Representatives.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The Republican–Union coalition lost seats but retained an overall majority against the backdrop of the American Civil War.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] In the first real test of opposition to the Lincoln administration, the Democratic Party made large gains in these and concurrent elections held in 1862 and 1863 but failed to take control of the House.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Much of the campaign focussed on emancipation and Lincoln's handling of the war.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, weeks before critical races in Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania, (October 14) and New York (November 3).
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Democrats denounced emancipation as tyrannical and a threat to white supremacy.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Democratic election propaganda charged their opponents with bloodlust and religious fanaticism and made frequent appeals to anti-Black racism.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] While Radical Republicans defended the measure, others felt compelled to distance themselves from the president's policy.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] In Indiana and Ohio, the Union Party downplayed the slavery issue.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The issue was particularly troublesome for Unionists in the border states.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Kentucky's Union Democratic Party disavowed the proclamation ahead of congressional elections held in August 1863.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] In Maryland and Missouri, Unionists welcomed emancipation in principle but divided over questions over gradual versus immediate abolition and the enlistment of Black soldiers.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Other issues impacted the election, including Lincoln's suspension of *habeas corpus*, conscription, and the progress of the war.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Inconclusive Union victories at Antietam, Corinth, and Perryville contributed to a perception that the administration's military strategy was ineffective.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Democrats charged the administration with subordinating the restoration of the Union to the radical social policy of the abolitionist movement.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] During this election, the Republican Party formed a coalition with War Democrats and border state unionists who supported the war effort.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] In most states, this coalition was known as the Union Party or as the Republican–Union Party.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] In parts of New England and the Upper Midwest, pro-administration candidates still called themselves Republicans.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The Missouri Unionists were known as the Emancipation Party and split between Immediate and Gradual Emancipationists during this election.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The Republican–Union coalition became the basis for the National Union Party which contested the next election.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] While contemporary observers interpreted the elections as a "severe reproof" of the administration, the results of the elections were inconclusive.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Democrats flipped more than 30 seats compared to the last election, while Republican–Unionists suffered serious losses across the Lower North.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The strong showing for Union candidates in the border states, however, salvaged the Republican–Unionist majority.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Among the defeated Republican–Unionists was the incumbent speaker of the House of Representatives Galusha A.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Grow, who lost his Pennsylvania district to a Democratic challenger.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] This was the last election in which a sitting speaker of the House was defeated for re-election until 1994, when George Nethercutt defeated Tom Foley in Washington's 5th congressional district.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Reapportionment took place following the 1860 United States census.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The 1862 apportionment act increased the size of the House to 241 seats from 233.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Fifty-eight seats were vacant due to secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Three seats were transferred from Virginia to West Virginia following the latter's admission on June 20, 1863.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] One seat was allocated to Nevada upon its admission on October 31, 1864, increasing the size of the House to 242 seats and the number of elected members to 184.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Special elections were held in 1862 and 1863 to fill 12 vacancies in the 37th Congress and four vacancies in the 38th Congress.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Alabama did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Arkansas held no elections in 1862 or 1863 as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Late elections were held in 1864, but the elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] California elected its members on September 2, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Voters chose three members on a statewide general ticket to represent the state's at-large congressional district.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Connecticut elected its members April 6, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Delaware elected its member on November 1, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Florida did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Georgia did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Illinois elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Indiana elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Iowa elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Kansas elected its member on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Whereas the Union Party replaced the Republicans in most states during the war, the Kansas Republican Party remained active.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] In a factional schism, opponents of U.S. senator Jim Lane split from the Republican Party in 1862 to form the Union Party with the support of the state's Democrats.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Parrott for Congress, was not affiliated with the national Republican–Union coalition and broke apart during the 1864 presidential election.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Kentucky elected its members on August 3, 1863, after the new term began but before Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Louisiana held no elections for the 38th Congress in 1862 or 1863 as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Late elections were held on September 5, 1864, but the elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Maine elected its members on September 8, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Maryland elected its members on November 3, 1863, after the new term began but before Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Massachusetts elected its members on November 1, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Massachusetts Republicans resisted incorporation into the Union Party in 1861 and 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Conservative Republicans, former Whigs, and Democrats attended the state convention of the Constitutional Union Party which nominated candidates for the upcoming elections.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The convention called itself the People's Party in order to attract votes from Democrats.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Conservative former Whigs and Republicans in the party expressed strong support for the Lincoln administration during the spring and summer under the belief that the president firmly opposed emancipation.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The Preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, issued less than two weeks before the state convention met, helped to divide and defeat the new party in its infancy.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Michigan elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] A Democratic proposal for a bipartisan Union ticket was rejected by the Radical leadership of the Michigan Republican Party.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The Democrats went ahead with plans for a Union state convention and called themselves Union Democrats or Fusionists during the campaign in hopes of attracting votes from disaffected Conservative Republicans.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Some conservatives did support the Union ticket, which was disavowed by the Republican state committee.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Minnesota elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Mississippi did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Missouri elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Missouri Unionists contested this election as the Emancipation Party.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] The party was divided ideologically between conservative Claybanks, who favored a plan of gradual emancipation, and radical Charcoals, who supported immediate emancipation.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Louis, Gradual and Immediate Emancipationists ran opposing tickets.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Some sources list the Gradual Emancipation candidates as Republicans; however, the Republican state committee deliberately deemphasized old party labels in its call for the state convention which gave rise to the Emancipation Party.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] Francis Preston Blair Jr., the most prominent leader of the Antebellum Missouri Republican Party, was nominated on the Union Emancipation ticket in Missouri's 1st congressional district and contested the election as a Gradual Emancipationist.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] New Hampshire elected its members on March 10, 1863.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p01] New Jersey elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] New York elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] North Carolina did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Ohio elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Oregon elected its members on June 2, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Pennsylvania elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Rhode Island elected its members on April 1, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] South Carolina did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Tennessee did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Texas did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Vermont elected its members on September 1, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] The Restored Government of Virginia held elections in three districts on May 28, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] The elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] West Virginia elected its members on October 22, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] The state and its congressional districts had formed part of Western Virginia before being admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, with the consent of the Restored Government of Virginia.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] The West Virginian members were seated on December 7, 1863.
[src:american-civil-war/1862-congressional-elections-p02] Wisconsin elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Union Navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:american-civil-war/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
